[4] Liberia: Last Ebola patient
Date: Wed 4 Mar 2015
Source: StarAfrica, APA report [edited]
http://en.starafrica.com/news/liberia-to-discharge-last-ebola-patient-thursday.html


Liberia to discharge last Ebola patient Thursday [5 Mar 2015]
-------------------------------------------------------------
The head of Liberia's Ebola Incident Management System [IMS], assistant health minister Tolbert Nyenswah, has said that Liberia will on Thursday [5 Mar 2015] discharge its last Ebola patient from the Chinese Ebola Treatment Unit (ETU) in the Paynesville suburb of Monrovia. "There will be a discharge ceremony of the lone live confirmed Ebola case..." Nyenswah told reporters at the Information Ministry daily Ebola press conference in Monrovia on Wednesday [4 Mar 2015].

According to Nyenswah, the discharge of the lone case would indicate that the country is gradually moving towards its countdown that could possibly signify the end of the crisis, if citizens resist complacency. Quoting statistics from the IMS, he, however, noted that there are 102 Ebola contacts across the country, with nearly all of the ETUs nearing emptiness.

"13 of the 15 counties have completed more than 2 of their incubation periods without a single trace of any new case, which means, that most political sub-divisions of the county, except Montserrado and Margibi Counties, have gone 28 days or more without a confirmed case," he said. He stressed the need for residents to resist complacency as the country is close to defeating the Ebola virus disease. "We must remain on the alert by complying with all of the preventive measures," he said.

Last week, deputy information minister Isaac Jackson disclosed that there were 2 confirmed cases of Ebola in the 19 ETUs across the country.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[According to the New York Times [edited], 5 Mar 2015 (http://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/06/world/africa/last-ebola-patient-in-liberia-beatrice-yardolo-discharged-from-treatment.html), "If no new cases emerge, the epidemic in Liberia will be considered over officially on 4 Apr [2015], or 42 days after the last known infection. The 42-day marker is twice the longest incubation period for Ebola, 21 days.

Liberia has suffered the highest number of deaths during the epidemic, with 4117 recorded victims, according to the World Health Organization. More than 9800 people have died in total." ...

Also see: Washington Post, 7 Mar 2015: "The biggest threat to stopping Ebola is thinking that it's over now" (http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wonkblog/wp/2015/03/07/the-biggest-threat-to-stopping-ebola-is-thinking-that-its-over-now/).

Nonetheless, an exciting and hopeful headline; but for Liberia to remain free of Ebola, it will require vigilance and strict adherence to proper public health protocol as well as maintenance of the health care system, both challenging. - Mod.LK]

