[5] Ebola blood test problems
Date: Mon 2 Mar 2015
Source: Reuters [edited]
http://www.reuters.com/article/2015/03/02/us-health-ebola-guinea-exclusive-idUSKBN0LY20Y20150302


Ebola blood test problems using wrong tubes in Guinea centers
-------------------------------------------------------------
There were mistakes in dealing with Ebola blood tests in Jan-Feb 2015 which led to the release of at least 4 positive patients, 2 of whom later died, Guinea's anti-Ebola coordinator and other health officials said. The mistakes occurred at 2 different treatment centers. Dr Sakoba Keita, Guinea's anti-Ebola coordinator, confirmed the mistake had occurred. "This error was detected and the order was immediately given to withdraw the [incorrect] tubes and to find the patients in order to test them again," Keita said.

Health officials said the mistakes occurred when staff placed blood samples in the wrong test tubes, and took place in Coyah, where Cuban medics are supporting a government-run center, and in Conakry, where medical charity Medicins Sans Frontieres [MSF] runs a center at the Donka hospital complex. Patients were discharged from the centers in western Guinea, one of the biggest remaining Ebola hot spots in the region, after the test results came back negative. At least 6 patients were later found to be Ebola-positive when further tests were carried out, and 2 of them died, the officials said.

MSF said it discovered on 6 Feb 2015 that blood samples from 43 patients taken from its Donka center had been placed in tubes containing the blood-thinning drug heparin in green tubes, while those for Ebola are in red or purple. The World Health Organization (WHO) said staff taking samples had run out of the correct tubes and instead used the heparin tubes, without reporting it. When discovered, "MSF took the incident very seriously and immediately replaced the tubes and opened an investigation," said Rosa Crestani, MSF's emergency program coordinator. 3 of those tested were later discovered to be Ebola positive and recovered, she said. No one who came in contact with the trio contracted the disease.

At the Coyah center, Guinea's busiest Ebola facility, which is also supported by staff from the African Union, the samples of 9 people were accidentally placed in tubes also containing heparin, said another health official. The official said that after initially being found to be Ebola negative, 3 of the 9 later tested positive, of whom 2 died. No further cases among contacts of the 3 Ebola patients released from Coyah have been identified, he said.

WHO said the mistake was not detected in the Donka laboratory, which tested both sets of samples, where technicians had received a "huge amount of samples". The laboratory is run by Guinea and supported by the Institut Pasteur de Dakar -- a foundation created in 2009 by a statute signed between Senegal and France's Institut Pasteur.

Dr Dan Kelly, founder of the Wellbody Alliance providing healthcare in Sierra Leone, said it was not unusual for centers to run out of test tubes, but procedures existed. "Stock outs happen. What you are supposed to do is wait for the right colored tubes to arrive," he said. ...

[byline: Emma Farge]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
and
Roger Feldman
<promedrf@gmail.com>

[A number of questions are raised by this report, such as why did the labs themselves not immediately notify the director/manager of the lab as well as the testing lab to let them know there was a misuse of the tubes as indicated by color code? And one would have thought the testing lab would have noticed the problem since the tubes they received to test for virus would have had the wrong color. What brought this oversight to attention? It is concerning that similar problems occurred in 2 labs.

If the issue was a shortage of the correct tubes, it is important that this supply chain problem is addressed immediately. It is equally important that laboratory personnel be trained to understand the correct use of the different tubes, so that when there is a shortage, appropriate action is taken. - Roger Feldman & Mod.LK]

