Vaccines, drugs, technology
---------------------------
5 Mar 2015: United Nations health agency announces start of Ebola vaccine testing in worst-affected areas of Guinea
http://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=50252
[According to the WHO, Phase III vaccine trials in Guinea will start on 7 Mar 2015 for rVSV-ZEBOV (developed by the Public Health Agency of Canada; licensed to NewLink Genetics, a company which is developing immunotherapies, which is collaborating on the vaccine with Merck since November 2014). Trials involve the identification of a newly diagnosed Ebola case and the tracing of all his/her contacts. Contacts are vaccinated if they give their consent. "The objectives of the trial are 2-fold: to assess if the vaccine protects the contacts who were vaccinated and if vaccinating the contacts will create a buffer -- or ring -- of protected individuals around the index case to prevent further spread of the infection"]

5 Mar 2015: Researchers examine effect of experimental Ebola vaccine after high-risk exposure
http://medicalxpress.com/news/2015-03-effect-experimental-ebola-vaccine-high-risk.html
[In September 2014, a 44-year-old physician, while working in a Sierra Leone Ebola treatment facility, experienced a needle-stick injury; 43 hours later, after flying to the United States, he received an experimental Ebola vaccine (rVSV-ZEBOV). Subsequently, he did not develop Ebola, and there were strong immune responses after the vaccination]

[See L Lai; R Davey; A Beck, et al. Emergency postexposure vaccination with vesicular stomatitis virus-vectored Ebola vaccine after needlestick. JAMA. 2015; Preliminary communication. http://jama.jamanetwork.com/article.aspx?articleid=2195001: "The vaccine used was rVSV-ZEBOV, also called VSV [Delta] G-ZEBOV, (Public Health Agency Canada and NewLink Genetics Inc), a replicating, attenuated, recombinant vesicular stomatitis virus (serotype Indiana) whose surface glycoprotein gene was replaced by the Zaire Ebola virus glycoprotein gene (Kikwit strain). This vaccine has entered a clinical trial for the prevention of Ebola in West Africa -- see item above regarding rVSV-ZEBOV."

From http://www.doctorslounge.com/index.php/news/pb/53534 Health Net [edited]: Thomas Geisbert, PhD, a professor of microbiology and immunology at the University of Texas Medical Branch at Galveston, and also the author of an editorial accompanying the new study, said that "the article reinforces the need for fast-acting single-injection preventive vaccines to control and manage outbreaks." If proven safe and effective in humans, the single-dose shot "would have great utility for things like vaccinating health care workers and 1st responders, say, right before you put them on an airplane to go into the hot zone." -- Mod.LK]

7 Mar 2015: Ebola's low-down on high tech
http://www.economist.com/news/technology-quarterly/21645502-advanced-equipment-has-been-developed-help-protect-health-care-workers
[Advanced equipment has been developed to help protect health-care workers, but the gear may not be helpful in poor countries]

